graphy in New Brunswick that has existed not in isolation from the rest of Canada but often at the creative forefront of imagined alternatives in identity and citizenship. At a time when cultural industries are threatened by forces that seek to negate difference and impose uniformity, New Brunswick at the Crossroads provides an understanding of the intersection of cultures and social economies, contributing to critical discussions about what constitutes “the creative” in Canadian society, especially in rural, non-central spaces like New Brunswick.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCanadian literaturezNew BrunswickxHistory and criticism. 0aLiterature and societyzNew BrunswickxHistory. 4aLiterary Criticism: Canadian Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Canadian.2bisacsh  aAcadia.  aAcadian literature.  aAcadie.  aAtlantic Canada.  aAtlantic Canadian literature.  aChantal Richard.  aChristl Verduyn.  aDavid Creelman.  aGwendolyn Davies.  aMarie-Linda Lord.  aMaritime.  aNew Brunswick literature.  aNew Brunswick.  aRenaissance communities.  aThomas Hodd.  aTony Tremblay.  abi-culturalism.  abilingualism.  acreative communities.  acultural economy.  acultural geography.  acultural pluralism.  aculture.  aferment.  aliterary history.  aliterary sociology.  aregionalism.  arevision.1 aCreelman, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavies, Gwendolyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHodd, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLord, Marie-Linda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRichard, Chantal, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTremblay, Tony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voca